      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey professor, i'm struggling a bit with the concept of opportunity cost. can you give me a real-world example of how a company might face an opportunity cost when deciding between buying new machinery for a factory or spending that same money on a marketing campaign? thanks!",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Of course! Opportunity cost refers to the potential benefits an individual, organization, or society forgoes when choosing one alternative over another. In this case, if a company decides to buy new machinery, the opportunity cost would be the potential profits or market reach they might have gained from investing in a marketing campaign instead. Conversely, if they choose to fund the marketing effort, the opportunity cost would be the increased productivity or cost savings the new machinery could have provided in the long run. The decision hinges on which option the company believes will yield the best return on the investment.",
      "source": "target",
