    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i get the math part, but what if the costs aren't just numbers? like, what if there are invisible risks or things you just can't easily put a dollar sign on? how do companies account for those kinds of \"hidden\" losses?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Indeed, some opportunity costs are not easily quantifiable in financial terms, often due to their intangible nature. Companies may struggle to place a monetary value on factors such as employee morale, brand reputation, or consumer loyalty. To account for these \"hidden\" losses, businesses can perform a qualitative analysis alongside their quantitative assessments. Risk management techniques, such as sensitivity analysis, might be employed to understand the potential variability in outcomes under different scenarios. Companies may also apply a more conservative approach by considering the most pessimistic view of what could be gained from the foregone alternative. Additionally, experts within the field, such as risk managers or brand consultants, may conduct specialized studies or offer insights that help companies make more informed decisions when facing non-numerical factors as part of their opportunity cost assessments.",
